1.  For this example, make a company folder (example: C:\Joe's Art Co)

2.  Open the "Joe's Art Co" folder and make a folder inside that folder called "Jan Comic Book 2000". This is your project folder. Feel free to substitute these folder names for names that better suite your needs.

3.  eBook 4 Sale comes with sample bitmap files to give you something to experiment with. Copy these files to your project folder "Jan Comic Book 2000". You can find these files in the eBook 4 Sale application folder  C:\Program Files\eBook4Sale\Sample eComic Book. 
     These files are:
     Sample Page001.gif
     Sample Page002.gif
     Sample Page003.gif
     Sample Page004.gif
     Sample Page005.gif
     Sample Page006.gif
     Sample startup.gif
     Sample TileBack.gif

4.  Run the eBook 4 Sale program if it's not already running.

5.  Let's start by creating a new project. Use your mouse to click on the "File" menu and then select the "New Project" menu option.

6.  Use the "Save In:" combo box to make your way over to your project folder (example: C:\Joe's Art\Jan Comic Book 2000).

7.  In the "File Name:" edit field, type in a project name. Name it anything you want or type in "Jan Comic."

8.  The "Project Preferences" window should now pop up. Feel free to fill in the "Reg. Fee:" and the "Sales Tax:" edit fields and any of the other information and click OK. Change the "Reg. No." edit field to 12345 just to keep it simple for this example. The "Project Preferences" window is  covered in greater depth under the "Project Preferences" section of this help file.

9.  Let's now add some pages. Click on the "Project" menu and then click on the "Add Page(s)" menu option. eBook 4 Sale considers each bitmap or text file a page.

10. Have file "Sample Page001.bmp" to "Sample Page006.bmp" selected. Do not select the "Sample startup.bmp" or the "Sample TileBack.GIF" file. eBook 4 Sale adds files in alphabetical order which is why you need to number the pages 001, 002 and so on because if you just number them 1, 2, 3 and so on, the file Page10 will list before Page1, but if they are numbered Page001, Page010, they will list in the proper order.

11. Click on the "Open" button to load all these images. All the image files you select will be loaded in alphabetical order. Depending on the size, format and number of files selected, the loading process may take a second or two because each file that is loaded  is being checked.

12. You'll now be looking at the very last page in this project. Click on the arrow buttons to go from page to page.

13. Under the "Project" menu you will find two menu options you can experiment with, "Move Current Page" and "Delete Current Page." Feel free to move any of the pages around and delete one of the pages if you want.

14. Let's add the startup screen by clicking on the "File" menu and then select the "Preferences..." menu option.

15. In the "Build Preferences:" group, click on the "Select bitmap for  startup screen" check box.

16. Select the "Sample startup.bmp" file and click on the "Open" button to use this bitmap file as your startup screen. A startup screen gives your program a more polished look.

17. You'll now notice that the "Select bitmap for startup screen" check box is selected. Clicking on this check box again unselects the bitmap file that was chosen for the startup screen.

18. Now click on the "Select Background Tile Bitmap" and select the "Sample TileBack.gif" file. This is the graphic that will tile the  background to give your program an even more professional look.

19. Click OK in the  "Project Preferences" window to save your changes. Now would be a good time to save your project file, so click on the "File" menu and then select the "Save" menu option.

21. Click on the "Project" menu and then select the "Include Startup Info Screen" menu option. This is for information you want your potential customer to know about. What you could put here is your Copyright information, price of your ebook, information about you and your  company and so on. In the "Info Window Caption" edit field, enter in "Helpful Hint". In the "Info Window Title" enter in "What You Should Know" and for the "Info Text" edit field, enter in some misc information about you. Click OK.

22. Click on the "Project" menu and then select the "Include Order Form Info Screen" menu option. This is for additional information you want  your potential customer to know about ordering your ebook. What you could put here is information about ordering, price of your ebook, and so on. In the "Info Window Caption" edit field, enter in "Helpful Hint". In the "Info Window Title" enter in "How To Order" and for the "Info Text" edit field, enter in some misc information about ordering your ebook. Click OK. 

20. We are now ready to build the program. Please keep in mind that the sample files can only be used for experimentation and can not be used in part or whole in any way in your own projects. To build the program, Click on the "File" menu and then click on the "Build EXE" menu option. You could also click on the "Run Project" menu option to run your ebook.

21. The file that has been generated is yours to distribute. Note: The program generated by the shareware version of eBook 4 Sale will only run on your computer. Only licensed users of eBook 4 Sale can distribute the generated executable created by eBook 4 Sale.

22. That's it in a nutshell. Read the "Preferences" section of this help file for more information on the different program preference options.

You have created your first ebook (unless this is a refresher course). You will also notice that it is a program file. One file for your customers to download and run. This is what will also make it easy for your ebook to make it's way around the web.
