If reading the below scanning instructions leaves you confused, that is because you may not have any image editing experience. No need to worry, there are books on the subject you can purchase from your local book store. Adobe PhotoShop is a great image-editing tool and there are plenty of books on the subject.

One question you need to ask yourself before you start scanning is,  how big should the final image size be? What you want to do is scan your images in big, back up the files and then size down a copy of the original to the final size you plan on using. If you're new to scanning, this could be a tough one to get a handle on. Regardless of what resolution you scan an image in at, the basic unit of measurement is pixels wide by pixels tall. You want your final image to be a size that will be comfortable for most people viewing the artwork. If it's too small, you'll miss out on the detail and if it is too big, your customer will have to do too much scrolling, and that's no fun. Another problem with your images being too big is that the size of your final ebook file could be too large for most people to download. To help figure this out, let's look at the resolution your computer is currently running at. The most common resolutions are 640 x 480, 800 x 600, 1024 x 768, 1280 x 1024, and some are even higher. These numbers are in pixels wide by pixels tall. You can find this information by clicking on your Start button/Settings/Control Panel/Display/Settings tab. The "Desktop area" will show what resolution you are currently in.

Let's pick a resolution we think most computers are set at, and my guess is 800 x 600. If you had to, you could size your images down so that they would fall into this range but we still need the images to be a little smaller then 800 x 600 so a good compromise is about 700 x 500. Now that we have a range to work with, your image may be too small if we want to confine it to this box. The solution is to have it so that you (in most cases) only have to scroll in one direction. When we are reading text files or web surfing, we are only scrolling down. It would be a drag if we had to scroll both ways all the time instead just one. So let's say your images are taller then they are wider. What you could do is have the width of your image fall around 500 pixels wide while the height could go well beyond 800 pixels high. The height no longer matters because having to scroll down to see the rest is okay.

If you plan on having a startup screen image and a background tile image, these images are usually small because the nature of the artwork doesn't lend itself to being big. These images usually fall well below the 640 x 480 image size. To help you get a feel for the size of these images, open the Sample startup.gif and the Sample TileBack.gif file in your image editor to see what the sizes are. Also, it wouldn't be a bad idea to open the Sample Page001.gif file in your image editor to see the size of the file.

Let's say there is text in your scans because this is a comic book. Many times the text may not be readable so what we can do is, after we have scanned in the artwork, re-add the text by using the text features in your image editing software. If there is a lot of text this could be tedious but nonetheless, has to be done. The other option is to have the text in your artwork a little bigger than you would normally have it so that when it is scanned, it is still readable.

Another thing to watch for is to make sure you scan in your artwork straight. This may take some practice and it may never be absolutely straight; all you can do is get it as close as you can.

Now, what if your artwork is too big for your scanner? You could have it scanned by a graphic arts house which will cost you some money. Another thing you could try is to scan it in pieces and then assemble the pieces in your image editing software. This is much trickier to do but can be done.

After you scan in your artwork, you'll end up with some imperfections due to the process of scanning. This is where you clean up the image in your image editing software and remove any blemishes you may find. You can even take this opportunity to fine-tune your artwork by adding a little more contrast, make the colors brighter, and sharpening the image.

The final consideration is, what file format to save the image file in. You'll want to use a compressed file format like *.GIF or *.JPG. If you're scanning in line drawings or comic-type art, chances are you may be able to index the image to a 256-color image and save it as a *.GIF. You'll always get a better compression ratio with *.GIF over *.JPG. If you're artwork is a more continuous tone, like a photograph, then keeping the image as an *.RGB file and saving it as a *.JPG is your best choice. *.GIFs are for images with 256 or less colors and *.JPG is for images with more than 256 colors. Do some experiments to see which format works best for you. Keep in mind the *.JPG compression algorithm works by not saving all the color information so you always get back less then what you originally started out with. This is why you never want to save your original big files as *.JPG. Also, depending on how hard you compress the image, the final image could look really bad, so you don't want to compress your *.JPGs too hard. This will require some experimentation.

To recap, here are the steps to take when scanning in your artwork.

1.  Scan in your artwork 3 to 4 times bigger than you currently need it. That way you can always go back to the big one and size it down to your current needs. Only size down, never size up.

2.  Clean up the artwork by removing pits, blemishes and any other imperfections that you can see. This is also a good time to enhance the scan by adding more contrast, brightening up the colors and any other enhancement you can think of. This is NOT the time to sharpen the image, that comes later.

3.  You now want to back-up these images. A removeable drive or a writeable CD is a good way to go. Never save your originals as *.JPG files.

4.  Now that your original scans are safely backed up, you are now free to size a copy of the image files for your use. After you figure out the desired size, size your images down and then sharpen them. If there is text and it's not all that  readable, this is when you would redo the text. The reason we don't redo the text when the files are big is because by the time we size the image down, the text may not be readable and we would have to do it all over again.

5.  The last step is to save your file in the desired file format, be it *.GIF or *.JPG.

