If you're new to making ebooks, putting a price on your work is a hard thing to do. Authors tend to underprice their work. Having an ebook that is too cheap is just as bad as one that is too expensive. Inexpensive doesn't mean more sales. Let's say, for example, your ebook is priced under $5.00. My opinion is that the price is way too low and it's not so much as the price itself as it is what the price conveys to the customer. They may think, "If it's that cheap, it may not be worth it." If your customer is going to pull out their checkbook or go online to purchase with a credit card, the price needs to validate the time spent doing one of these two tasks. They may find to easier to spend $10.00 then it is to spend $5.00 or less. This is a very different concept than what you are normally used to. They can justify the time it takes to spend $10.00 but they may not be able to justify the time it takes to spend $5.00 or less. Also, people like round numbers, so instead of prices like $7.99, $3.55 etc., a straight $5.00, $10.00, $15.00 will work better. If you're going to put a price tag of about $7.50 on your ebook, you might as well just sell it for $10.00.

The price of your ebook will not motivate the customer to purchase it; price will only motivate them NOT to purchase. For example, someone downloads your ebook and decides that they really want it. The price could be anywhere from $5.00 to $20.00. As long as the price is within their comfort zone, they will not have a problem purchasing it. Let's say their comfort zone is between $5.00 and $20.00 and your ebook is priced higher than $20.00. They have already decided they want your ebook but now they have to convince themselves to pay an amount higher then what they feel is a fair price. Now they have to decide how badly they want it.  Everyone's comfort zone is a little different but what you are trying to do is to pick the highest price that will be within enough comfort zones to yield the most (gross) sales. For example, at $5.00 each you sell on average 100 books a month, which yields a total sales of $500.00. Let's say you sold the same ebooks at $10.00 each but you sell 70 books a month on average, which yields a total sales of $700.00. You've made $200 dollars more selling less number of books. Keep in mind, every order you receive is time spent processing the order, so that's also less time spent for more money.

Please use the above as a guideline to help in pricing your ebooks. Don't be afraid to experiment.

