For my business, I took the option of processing the credit cards myself. Below is information on how to get started.

Being able to accept credit cards for purchases is an easy thing to set up, however because of the nature of the beast, it takes a little bit of research and time to do so.  Also, if you are new to the business of taking credit cards, and don't know a thing about how to get started, the following information should clear up some questions you may have and get you headed in the right direction.

The first thing you need to decide is what credit cards you want to accept.  You can do just one or you can do them all - it's up to you.  I take the main ones - Visa, MasterCard, Discover and AmericanExpress.  Once you have made that decision, it's time to do your research.

Before I explain the research process, let me explain a little bit about these four main credit cards.  Visa and MasterCard are usually associated together and have certain requirements to get started.  First, you must be a legally, licensed business before you will even be considered for their service.  This means that, if you have not registered your business in your state, you will have to do so by going to your local County Clerk's office to fill out the proper registration application.  Since you would be processing these cards online, you will need a business checking account (not a savings account) for your deposits to be made directly to by Visa/MasterCard.  Note:  Discover and AmericanExpress do not have those requirements; they will set you up no matter what!  And, you don't need to open a business checking account.  However, because Visa and MasterCard are the two most widely distributed credit cards around the world, it would be silly not to accept them!  So your caught in a Catch-22 situation.

Now, one of the terms you will be seeing a lot of in business is "Merchant."  That is what you are considered - the Merchant.  It is now time to do some research to check on "Merchant Services."  You can do a couple of things here.  One is to call the bank where you have accounts (savings, checking, etc.) set up and ask them for Merchant Account information.  They will then probably give you a separate phone number where you will get in touch with someone in this field.  When you finally talk to someone, here are some questions you need to consider:

1)  What credit cards can they set you up with?

2)  What discount rate can they offer you for these credit cards? Note:  Discount rates are the percentages the bank or merchant service charges for processing your credit cards.  They usually depend on your average ticket item charge (such as $5.00, $10.00, etc.).  The rates may range anywhere from 3% to 4% and vary with individual credit card.  So, if you process an order for $10.00 and the discount rate is 3%, the amount of $9.70 will be deposited to your account for that order.

3)  Do they have processing equipment that you can rent or buy? Note:  I use a Verifone Tranz 330 processing terminal that I purchased from my merchant service provider.  Some will rent them to you, others require you to purchase them. There are many types of terminals available; all you need is something basic to key in your customer's credit card number to get it authorized.  There's no need for anything fancy like one that prints - they are much more expensive.

4)  Find out if they have a setup fee and/or monthly fee for providing the service in addition to the discount rates.

5)  Do you have to have a "business" account or can the deposits be made directly to your personal checking or savings account?  If you need a "business" account, get information on the different accounts available.  There are many different types of business accounts and you'll want to go with one that best suits your needs.

These are just a few important things to consider when you start to do your research. Another important thing to know (which I did not when I first started) is that, since Visa and MasterCard are the largest of the credit cards, you will want to look at merchant account providers who process those credit cards.  American Express and Discover are two totally separate entities, and although you can go through them for processing and terminals, etc., they cannot process any other credit cards but their own!  Now, you're not going to want to have to buy a terminal for each credit card you're interested in accepting, right!  However, the merchant service provider for Visa and MasterCard CAN usually process all other credit cards using one terminal.  Since it's all computerized through the phone lines, they have a way to route each entered credit card number to it's proper account provider.  You will, however, need to set up a merchant account with each of the other credit card companies individually before your processing service can process them.

One more way to do research is to check out the web.  Just do a search for "Merchant Services" and you'll get a whole bunch of websites dedicated to giving you information on what they can offer you.  Many major banks have websites, but also, so do some fly-by-night processing companies offering you the "lowest rates you'll find anywhere!"  That may be true, but you're going to want to go with a company that you can depend on to be there whenever you have questions or problems as well as one who will work for you and with you to give you what your company needs.

Here are some common problems that you may come across with taking credit cards; most of them are very easy to handle.

1)  The same way a customer may type in an incorrect e-mail address, they can also mistype their credit card number and/or expiration date.  If you are using a terminal to process your orders, the terminal will display a message that will let you know that the number you have typed in is incorrect.  Double-check the number to make sure that you typed it in correctly and if you did, you'll just have to e-mail the customer requesting that they re-submit the order again.  NOTE: Be sure to inform them never to send credit card information through regular e-mail; it is not secure!

2)  Authorization Declined.  Sometimes someone will submit a credit card that has already exceeded it's limit hoping to get an extra purchase out of it.  Your terminal will also pick this up and display a message.  Again, you'll have to e-mail your customer of the problem and suggest they either send the order again using another credit card or sending the order by mail paying with a check or money order.

3)  Chargebacks.  This rarely happens, but when it does, it's very frustrating.  These you will get in the mail and it means that the owner of the card used to purchase one of your products is disputing that purchase.  It usually means that someone unauthorized used the card to purchase something (stolen card or card number or one of the owner's children decides to buy something with mommy or daddy's card without permission).  You will be requested to show proof of the transaction (such as the signature of the purchaser, or proof of delivery of product to given address). Well, guess what!?  You won't have any of that because you're an online business who does not have anything tangible that is being sold or signature on file.  In this case, you'll just have to bite the big one and count it as a loss because your account will be debited.  With all of the sales you get, this really never counts for much.

